flowRoot.flowPara: - analyze data in a layout ready for sharing and anonymizied (where possible)
- try to collect as much detail about your acquisition as possible (sequence protocols, DICOMs, associated QA data, ...)
- try to adhere to some convention on file hierarchy, e.g. of openfmri.org
- upload your data to some public data hosting portal (e.g. crcns.org, openfmri.org, etc.)
Can you imagine your research without Open Source Software?
Do you acknowledge the people who created your favorite toolbox?
Have you ever coded sometehing just to find out it existed already?
Often users are not aware of all the methods they're using in their analysis, and thus can't properly acknowledge the software and method developers
Without adequate citations for softwares and methods, funding agencies receive the false impression that scientific software is not important enough to be funded
Many times people (i.e., Ph.D. students) have to "re-implement the wheel" creating short-lived projects instead of contributing to existing ones, just because they might not know they exists!
Solution: a simple framework in Python to embed references in the code
software, methods, and data you use
Yaroslav O. Halchenko, Matteo Visconti di Oleggio Castello
Dept. of Psychological and Brain Sciences, Dartmouth College
